Hi,
there should be "/nbd/<str>" instead of "/nbd/0", because currently only slot_0 is available in VirtualMedia.
If I changed it, there's no path to pass the <str> part to the onOpen caller.  We would need to add it, which I intend on doing in the next patch.

I'm not sure if I understand the problem with passing the <str> part. It seems to be already handled in afterGetManagedObjects function (https://gerrit.openbmc.org/plugins/gitiles/openbmc/bmcweb/+/466bed5807041334a85955aa220f795047155420/include/vm_websocket.hpp#429 ). Keeping this as it is here will break our virtual media implementation after bmcweb bump, as we will be able to mount only one device.
Put back <str>
To be clear, I had a misunderstanding about how that worked.  You're right, it looks like it does work.

Directives with BMCWEB_ENABLE_VM_NBDPROXY flag should be changed to condition:
if constexpr (bmcwebVirtualMediaProvider == "virtual-media"), because BMCWEB_ENABLE_VM_NBDPROXY doesn't exist anymore.
Done

There should be a namespace change from ndb_proxy to obmc_vm:
crow::obmc_vm::requestRoutes(app);
Done
Hi @Ed, just confirm that this code is used by us (Ampere). If you remove this code, the feature Virtual Media via Redfish will not work anymore.

> If you remove this code, the feature Virtual Media via Redfish will not work anymore.

Virtual media via Redfish isn't under either option, so I'm not sure what you mean.  Also, Redfish virtual media never worked upstream, as it relied on Intels virtual media implementation that never made it through code review.

It's good to hear someone is relying on this though.  What would you like to see happen here?  have you followed any of the discussions around the new VM implementation?

Hi @Ed, I mean if you remove this flag `BMCWEB_ENABLE_VM_NBDPROXY` and its related code the feature virtual media via redfish will not work anymore.
https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/master/redfish-core/lib/managers.hpp#L1936
https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/master/redfish-core/include/redfish.hpp#L193

Understood.  Re-asking my question:

What would you like to see happen here? (in the virtual media code).
@Hieu?
Hi @Ed, sorry for late response. LGTM.

I've a question here. Why can't we consider using Intel's virtual-media instead of jsnbd? https://github.com/Intel-BMC/virtual-media Based on my understanding It supports both legacy and proxy mode implementations.

> I've a question here. Why can't we consider using Intel's virtual-media instead of jsnbd? https://github.com/Intel-BMC/virtual-media Based on my understanding It supports both legacy and proxy mode implementations.

the Intel virtual media is one of the two that are being combined.
